Security Wire Perspectives, June 9, 2005
In-depth analysis, opinion and insight.

This issue is brought to you by: 
Consul risk management

IN THIS ISSUE:
*Editor's Note

*Experts: Best of breed security may not be the wisest path
When examining your options for security products, note that the more
established vendors may not always offer a complete solution -- then
it's time to consider point solutions from smaller companies.

*Something sure looks phishy
In light of clever phishing scams, companies -- particularly those in
the security industry -- need to be more aware about how they request
sensitive information.

*A look at the news from SearchSecurity.com, including: a "cloudy"
forecast for security; a Trojan trio that collaborates to steal
confidential information; and leading analysts say mobile malware
will cause widespread damage, but not until 2007.

=====================================================
SECURITY WIRE PERSPECTIVES IS SPONSORED BY: Consul risk management

Gartner and Consul Compliance Advisory Series 

To maximize corporate governance, an organization must implement a
framework for identifying and managing risk, without straining the
business and limiting productivity. Join Gartner and for an
educational discussion on: establishing and maintaining a risk
management culture; aligning IT resources and investments with a
common risk framework; and creating a holistic compliance and risk
architecture. 

Register Today!
http://searchSecurity.com/r/0,,42262,00.htm?track=NL-358&ad=519329

=====================================================
EDITOR'S NOTE

We don't hear as much about hype in the security industry these days,
but here comes FUD-buster analyst firm Gartner Group to tell us which
security threats aren't as huge as some want to believe. Check out
our story on SearchSecurity.com to find out what made the list.
You'll find it at:
http://searchsecurity.techtarget.com/originalContent/0,289142,sid14_gci1096135,00.html.?track=NL-358&ad=519329

Elsewhere during the Gartner IT Security Summit, analysts decided
it's time for admins to get their head in the clouds
[http://searchsecurity.techtarget.com/originalContent/0,289142,sid14_gci1095562,00.html?track=NL-358&ad=519329 ] and said compliance shouldn't be a primary security driver [http://searchsecurity.techtarget.com/originalContent/0,289142,sid14_gci1095317,00.html?track=NL-358&ad=519329 ]. Inside each article is a Sound Off link where you can share your thoughts on analyst opinions. 

Also, don't forget to take our latest minipoll on which of the five
over-hyped security threats reported by Garter is the most overblown
[http://searchsecurity.techtarget.com/news/0,289141,sid14,00.html?track=NL-358&ad=519329 ].

--Shawna McAlearney, editor, Security Wire Perspectives 

=====================================================
A READ ON THE NEWS

*Experts: Best of breed security may not be the wisest path
By Shawna McAlearney, News Editor

Today's information security professionals face tough decisions when
trying to identify and deploy the correct security products for their
enterprise environments -- "Should I use another product from a
current best of breed provider or take a chance on an emerging vendor
with more targeted technology?" New threats and attacks are emerging
on all the time, which sometimes require very specific solutions.
Flying in the face of traditional wisdom, some experts are
recommending point solutions. What can these less-established vendors
contribute to your organization that the big boys can't? Find out:
http://searchsecurity.techtarget.com/originalContent/0,289142,sid14_gci1096619,00.html?track=NL-358&ad=519329

=====================================================
Don't miss the latest article!

MacIntosh vs. Windows: Choosing to take a bite of the Apple

Hardly a day goes by without hearing about a new worm, virus or other
attack targeting vulnerabilities in a Windows OS, wasting admins'
time with patching and/or cleaning their networks. Cybersecurity guru
and noted author Winn Schwartau switches from Windows to Mac and says
it may solve his security ills. Installments in this ongoing series
will be posted each week so don't forget to check back, it may
benefit your organization.

This week:
Mad as Hell IV: Security basics for Ma&Pa 
http://searchsecurity.techtarget.com/columnItem/0,294698,sid14_gci1096261,00.html?track=NL-358&ad=519329
Schwartau takes a look at the three fingered reboot salute and the
tenets of CIA.  

Mad as Hell archive:
http://searchsecurity.techtarget.com/general/0,295582,sid14_gci1094430,00.html?track=NL-358&ad=519329

=====================================================
SOUND BYTES

*Something sure looks phishy
By Clay Ruth, Contributing Writer

Phishing scams are increasingly clever, but it still came as a
surprise to one security professional to receive an e-mail from a
leading security vendor requesting detailed information through an
insecure channel. Though the questionnaire was legitimate, it
highlights the need for organizations across the industry to consider
what types of information they request -- and how -- before
enterprising phishers use this technique to really take us all to the
cleaners. Find out how one expert was nearly fooled into offering up
information on his company network:
http://searchsecurity.techtarget.com/columnItem/0,294698,sid14_gci1096504,00.html?track=NL-358&ad=519329

=====================================================
SearchSecurity.com's Web Security School

How well do you know Web security? If you think you're an expert,
take this quiz. If you can't ace this exam, we recommend you come to
SearchSecurity.com's free Web Security School. You'll learn how to
harden a Web server and apply countermeasures to prevent hackers from
wreaking havoc with your Web site. Guest instructor Michael Cobb,
author of "IIS Security," guides you through the three lessons. Each
includes an on-demand webcast, technical paper, quiz and handy
checklists. CISSPs and SSCPs earn one CPE credit per webcast.

http://searchsecurity.techtarget.com/general/0,295582,sid14_gci1080309,00.html?track=NL-358&ad=519329&promo 

